<https://colonial-heritage.triply.cc/nmvw/id/object/RV-2043-36> <https://colonialcollections.nl/schema#description> "Bowl, probably by Tonita Martinez Roybal; San Ildefonso Pueblo; ca. 1920\r\nPottery, pigment; 7,2 c 23,1 cm.\r\nRMV 2043-36; Postma collection, 1920\r\n\r\nLike the preceding jar, this black-on-red bowl was probably made and painted by Tonita Martinez Roybal. Also like the jar, the painted designs have no symbolic meaning, with one exception. The stepped motifs connected by a line drawn through the center of the bowl represent clouds. These and many other references to water were commonly depicted on pots both ceremonial and domestic.\r\n\r\nSmall bowls such as this are also linked to pottery revival at San Ildefonso. Crescencio Martinez and Julian Martinez (husband of Maria Martinez) both assisted archaeologists during excavations of ancestral Tewa sites on the nearby Pajarito Plateau. During those excavations both painters saw hundreds of jars and bowls. Documented pots show that as early as 1908 Julian copied the ancient pottery designs onto bowls made by Maria, and he continued to paint some ancient motifs throughout his career.\r\n\r\nJulian, Crescencio, Tonita, and other painters borrowed ideas freely from other potters at San Ildefonso and from potters in other communities. Around 1920 Tonita saw pottery made by the Hopi-Tewa potter Nampeyo or perhaps photographs of Nampeyo’s work, and she copied Nampeyo’s so-called “eagle tail” design many times, mixing it with motifs from pots made at Acoma and elsewhere. The design on this bowl does not appear to have been inspired by another artist, but its layout and execution display mastery of the craft: every potter says that painting a concave surface is very difficult.\r\n\r\nThe bowl is perfectly round, and its rim is of even thickness. Pueblo pottery is made by the ancient coil-and-scrape method, so it seems amazing that potters such as Tonita and Maria could shape pots so well. On bowls made by these two masters, one can reach around the rim with thumb and forefinger and pinch the pot while pulling the fingers over the walls, demonstrating that the thickness is absolutely uniform.\r\n\r\nToday we marvel at these vessels as works of art, but their makers struggled to sell them. The market in 1920 was little different than it had been in 1880; Pueblo pottery was abundant and inexpensive. Kenneth Chapman, who became instrumental in reviving pottery traditions in several Pueblo communities, noted that in 1920 potters at San Ildefonso – including Maria and Julian Martinez – still used farm wagons to take pottery to Santa Fe to sell for a mere pittance. On one occasion that year he encountered Tonita in Santa Fe. She was disheartened because she had been unable to sell two pots that she had been peddling door-to-door. Without adequate demand for their work, these potters often sold quantities of pottery for small change to curio dealers in Santa Fe well into the 1920s.\r\n\r\nChapman and others in Santa Fe worked tirelessly to promote Pueblo pottery. Chapman often made a point of paying more than the asking price for a pot, so long as the artist agreed to put even more effort into her next piece. Tonita, Maria, and others at San Ildefonso elevated the formerly utilitarian pottery to a fine art, and by the mid-1920s they signed their work. By 1930 Tonita and Juan Cruz, and Maria and Julian were making some of the most beautiful Pueblo pottery of all time. Their hard-earned fame resulted as much from perseverance as it did from perfecting their craft.\r\n\r\nJonathan Batkin\r\nWheelwright Museum of the American Indian, Santa FE, NM; 2015\r\n \r\n\r\nSAN ILDEFONSO. San Ildefonso kent een lange aardewerktraditie. Het hedendaags aardewerk ontwikkelde zich uit Powhoge polychroom, maar zwart-op-wit decoraties verdrongen het polychroom geleidelijk, zodat dit product de periode 1890-1920 typeert.\r\n\r\nHet aardewerk van San Ildefonso trok publieke aandacht door het werk van Maria Martinez (1887-1980) en haar echtgenoot Julian (1885-1943). Maria demonstraarde haar kunnen in 1904 op de Louisi-ana Purcha-se Exposition. Daarna werkten zij en Julian voor de Fred Harvey Compa-ny die de hotels, restaurants en winkeltjes langs de AT&SF Railroad exploiteerde. In dat verband toonde zij haar werk op de Panama-California Expo-sition in San Diego in 1915. Korte tijd later ontving zij reisgezelschappen van Fred Harvey thuis. Hun aardewerk werd nog meer gewild toen zij in 1919 een nieuwe decoratietechniek ontwikkelden van mat zwarte decoraties op een zwart glanzende achtergrond.\r\n\r\nMaria werkte later samen met haar zoon Popovi Da (1921-1971) die het zwart-op-siena aardewerk ontwikkelde. Kleinzoon Tony Da (geb. 1940) volgde in de voetstappen van zijn vader en grootouders. Albert Dunlap en zijn echtgenote Josephine Cordova ontwikkelden ook een populaire stijl, de wit-op-rood variëteit.\r\n\r\nRose Gonzales (1900-1989) ontwikkelde aardewerk waarvan in het oppervlak figuren werden uitgesneden in bas-relief. Dit leerde zij ook haar zoon Tse-Pe. Dora Gachupin (geb. 1939) en haar man Tsepe (geb. 1940) kregen een aantal kinderen waarvan Jennifer, Irene, Gerri en Canda-ce followed in de voetstappen van hun ouders volgden. Het relief-snijden leerden zij van hun moeder die de nadruk blijft leggen op kwaliteit in plaats van kwaliteit. De enige concessie die aan de markt wordt gedaan is het formaat van hun vaatwerk.\r\n\r\nEen andere beroemde pottenbakster was Blue Corn die meerdere stijlen beheerste. In de jaren zestig maakte zij kleine zwart-op-zwarte potjes waarin Ronson-tafelaanstekers pasten, een populair artikel." .
